occurrenceRemarks: The tree appeared to be healthy on inspection on 8 Feb 2018. Height 15 m via clinometer. Angophora subvelutina and A. floribunda appear to be hybridising at Euroka, based on leaf characters. From our inspection on 8 Feb 2018, we estimate that there are over 500 A. subvelutina, A. floribunda and intermediates growing at Euroka, occurring mainly along or near Euroka Creek and tributaries. In a sample of 60 of these plants, we recorded the following breakdown: A. velutina: 30, A. floribunda: 19, intermediates: 11 trees/saplings. We understand that there is a specimen of Angophora subvelutina at the National Herbarium of NSW collected at Euroka in the 1940s. We saw at least one very large, old A. subvelutina tree that probably predates European settlement. The A. subvelutina population at Euroka has clearly been there for a long time. The numbers of plants seen at the site on 8 Feb 2018, and the range of age classes present, indicate that it is still a viable population, despite the problem of hybridisation with A. floribunda.
habitat: Semi-cleared area in a circular valley on a volcanic diatreme. Euroka Creek and tributaries traverse the valley. Tree species in the remnant forest at Euroka include Allocasuarina torulosa, Casuarina cunninghamiana, Angophora bakeri, A. floribunda, A. subvelutina, Corymbia eximia, Eucalyptus agglomerata, E. beyeriana, E. deanei, E. eugenioides, E. fibrosa, E. punctata, E. saligna, E. tereticornis and Syncarpia glomulifera. The vegetation on this diatreme is notable for the diversity of tree species and for its Cumberland Plain influences.

habitat: There appears to be a large hybrid swarm in this area, especially where there are stands of Melaleuca species and the occasional Eucalyptus eugenoides. All of the apparent hybrids have very hairy buds, peduncles, pedicals and coarse narrow leaves but generally lack the upright leaf arrangement of A. inopina. Looking at 100 individuals over 1 ha, 3 individuals were found that approximated the decription of Angophora inopina.

habitat: Open forest with a moist understorey. Occurs mid-way up a gentle west facing slope. Substrate is sandy. Areas of sandstone bench occur in the locality, however soils at the site are not skeletal. Canopy: Bloodwood, Redgum, Ironbark 15-20% cover, 20m high. Mid: Casuarina, Red Ash, Acacia, 15%, 12-15 m high. Lower: Lantana, D. myoperoides, Red Ash, acacia 60% cover, 2m high, Acacia, Bracken, Bladey Grass, mixed native and introduced grasses and herbs including Kangaroo Grass, Barbed-wire Grass, Bidens pilosa. No bare ground, high leaf litter.

occurrenceRemarks: This tree was stunted and was approximately 5 to 10 m tall with rough bark. The leaves are small and are similar to A. bakeri or A. inopina. [Ex BIS 19000 - see specimen for additional notes and photo.]
habitat: Occurred only on ridge tops where basalt/andesite outcrops of carboniferous age were observed. An unusual community which was disturbed from cattle grazing in one area and contained a dense shrub layer on an adjoining property. The vegetaion community was dominated by this species with co-dominant of Eucalyptus albens and E. dwyeri on the more exposed upper ridges. The upper mid storey contained species such as Callitris endlicheri, C. glaucophylla and Brachychiton populneus. dominant shrub species included Dodonaea viscosa, Acacia decora, Notelaea microcarpa and Swainsona galegifolia. Ground layer species included Xanthorrhoea glauca subsp. angustifolia, Poa labillardierei, Aristida ramosa, Vittadinia cuneata and Desmodium brachypodium
